spec: as3496
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(asyncio)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 680 (as3496): __aenter__, __aexit__, __await__ dict-presence checks for asyncio types."
    - "asyncio.Lock defines __aenter__ and __aexit__ (true): Lock supports async with syntax."
    - "asyncio.Semaphore defines __aenter__ and __aexit__ (true): Semaphore supports async with syntax."
    - "asyncio.BoundedSemaphore does NOT define __aenter__ or __aexit__ in its own __dict__ (false): inherits from Semaphore."
    - "asyncio.Condition defines __aenter__ and __aexit__ (true): Condition supports async with syntax."
    - "asyncio.Future defines __await__ (true): Future objects are awaitable."
    - "asyncio.Task does NOT define __await__ in its own __dict__ (false): Task inherits from Future."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: asyncio.Task, asyncio.Future, asyncio.Event, asyncio.Lock, asyncio.Semaphore, asyncio.BoundedSemaphore, asyncio.Condition, asyncio.Queue, asyncio.PriorityQueue, asyncio.LifoQueue."
    - "Key finding (__aenter__): asyncio.Lock, asyncio.Semaphore, and asyncio.Condition each define __aenter__ in their own __dict__ (true). These three types directly implement the async context manager protocol — 'async with lock:', 'async with semaphore:', and 'async with condition:' are all valid idiomatic patterns. asyncio.BoundedSemaphore does NOT define __aenter__ in its own __dict__ (false) — it inherits __aenter__ from asyncio.Semaphore. asyncio.Task/Future: no __aenter__ in their own __dict__; these types are awaitable result handles, not async context managers. asyncio.Event: boolean-flag synchronization primitive; no __aenter__ defined. asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue: item stores with no __aenter__ in their own __dict__."
    - "Key finding (__aexit__): asyncio.Lock, asyncio.Semaphore, and asyncio.Condition each define __aexit__ in their own __dict__ (true). The __aexit__ implementations release the lock/permit/condition on exit from 'async with'. asyncio.BoundedSemaphore does NOT define __aexit__ in its own __dict__ (false) — it inherits __aexit__ from asyncio.Semaphore. All other asyncio types return false for __aexit__."
    - "Key finding (__await__): asyncio.Future defines __await__ in its own __dict__ (true). Future objects are awaitable — 'result = await future' is a core asyncio pattern. asyncio.Task does NOT define __await__ in its own __dict__ (false) — Task inherits __await__ from Future. All other asyncio types (Event, Lock, Semaphore, BoundedSemaphore, Condition, Queue, PriorityQueue, LifoQueue) return false for __await__."
    - "Critical distinction: asyncio.BoundedSemaphore.__aenter__ = false and asyncio.BoundedSemaphore.__aexit__ = false. BoundedSemaphore inherits the async context manager protocol from Semaphore. The async context manager dunders are absent from BoundedSemaphore's own __dict__ — they live in asyncio.Semaphore.__dict__."
    - "Critical distinction: asyncio.Task.__await__ = false and asyncio.Future.__await__ = true. Task is a subclass of Future and inherits __await__ from Future. The __await__ dunder is absent from Task's own __dict__."
    - "Cross-wave summary for asyncio subjects:"
    - "  Wave 656 (as3136): __call__/__len__/__getitem__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 657 (as3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 658 (as3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 659 (as3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 660 (as3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 661 (as3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 662 (as3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 663 (as3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 664 (as3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 665 (as3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 666 (as3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 667 (as3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 668 (as3316): __ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 669 (as3331): __iand__/__ior__/__ixor__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 670 (as3346): __neg__/__pos__/__abs__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 671 (as3361): __invert__/__floor__/__ceil__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 672 (as3376): __trunc__/__round__/__index__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 673 (as3391): __int__/__float__/__complex__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 674 (as3406): __bool__/__str__/__repr__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 675 (as3421): __hash__/__eq__/__lt__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 676 (as3436): __le__/__gt__/__ge__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 677 (as3451): __getitem__/__setitem__/__delitem__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 678 (as3466): __iter__/__next__/__len__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 679 (as3481): __enter__/__exit__/__call__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 680 (as3496): __aenter__/__aexit__/__await__ — Lock/Semaphore/Condition __aenter__=true, __aexit__=true; Future __await__=true; all others false."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __aenter__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__aenter__')
#
# asyncio.Lock defines __aenter__ in its own __dict__ (true).
#   'async with lock:' is the canonical pattern for async mutex usage.
#   Lock directly defines __aenter__ in its class __dict__.
# asyncio.Semaphore defines __aenter__ in its own __dict__ (true).
#   'async with semaphore:' is the canonical pattern for permit-count limiting.
#   Semaphore directly defines __aenter__ in its class __dict__.
# asyncio.BoundedSemaphore does NOT define __aenter__ in its own __dict__ (false).
#   BoundedSemaphore is a subclass of Semaphore and inherits __aenter__ from
#   Semaphore.__dict__. The dunder is absent from BoundedSemaphore.__dict__.
# asyncio.Condition defines __aenter__ in its own __dict__ (true).
#   'async with condition:' is the canonical pattern for condition variable usage.
#   Condition directly defines __aenter__ in its class __dict__.
# asyncio.Task/Future: awaitable result handles; not async context managers.
#   Neither defines __aenter__ in its own __dict__.
# asyncio.Event: boolean-flag synchronization primitive; no __aenter__ defined.
# asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue: item stores with no __aenter__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table as3496.aenter:
  description: "asyncio types __aenter__ dict-presence checks; wave 680"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: as3496

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["as3496001", operator.contains, [asyncio.Task.__dict__,             "__aenter__"], false]
    - ["as3496002", operator.contains, [asyncio.Future.__dict__,           "__aenter__"], false]
    - ["as3496003", operator.contains, [asyncio.Event.__dict__,            "__aenter__"], false]
    - ["as3496004", operator.contains, [asyncio.Lock.__dict__,             "__aenter__"], true]
    - ["as3496005", operator.contains, [asyncio.Semaphore.__dict__,        "__aenter__"], true]
    - ["as3496006", operator.contains, [asyncio.BoundedSemaphore.__dict__, "__aenter__"], false]
    - ["as3496007", operator.contains, [asyncio.Condition.__dict__,        "__aenter__"], true]
    - ["as3496008", operator.contains, [asyncio.Queue.__dict__,            "__aenter__"], false]
    - ["as3496009", operator.contains, [asyncio.PriorityQueue.__dict__,    "__aenter__"], false]
    - ["as3496010", operator.contains, [asyncio.LifoQueue.__dict__,        "__aenter__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __aexit__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__aexit__')
#
# asyncio.Lock defines __aexit__ in its own __dict__ (true).
#   The __aexit__ implementation releases the lock on exit from 'async with'.
#   Defined directly in Lock.__dict__.
# asyncio.Semaphore defines __aexit__ in its own __dict__ (true).
#   The __aexit__ implementation releases a permit on exit from 'async with'.
#   Defined directly in Semaphore.__dict__.
# asyncio.BoundedSemaphore does NOT define __aexit__ in its own __dict__ (false).
#   BoundedSemaphore inherits __aexit__ from Semaphore. The dunder is absent
#   from BoundedSemaphore.__dict__.
# asyncio.Condition defines __aexit__ in its own __dict__ (true).
#   The __aexit__ implementation releases the condition's underlying lock.
#   Defined directly in Condition.__dict__.
# asyncio.Task/Future/Event/Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue: no __aexit__ in
#   their own __dict__. None of these types are async context managers.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table as3496.aexit:
  description: "asyncio types __aexit__ dict-presence checks; wave 680"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: as3496

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["as3496011", operator.contains, [asyncio.Task.__dict__,             "__aexit__"], false]
    - ["as3496012", operator.contains, [asyncio.Future.__dict__,           "__aexit__"], false]
    - ["as3496013", operator.contains, [asyncio.Event.__dict__,            "__aexit__"], false]
    - ["as3496014", operator.contains, [asyncio.Lock.__dict__,             "__aexit__"], true]
    - ["as3496015", operator.contains, [asyncio.Semaphore.__dict__,        "__aexit__"], true]
    - ["as3496016", operator.contains, [asyncio.BoundedSemaphore.__dict__, "__aexit__"], false]
    - ["as3496017", operator.contains, [asyncio.Condition.__dict__,        "__aexit__"], true]
    - ["as3496018", operator.contains, [asyncio.Queue.__dict__,            "__aexit__"], false]
    - ["as3496019", operator.contains, [asyncio.PriorityQueue.__dict__,    "__aexit__"], false]
    - ["as3496020", operator.contains, [asyncio.LifoQueue.__dict__,        "__aexit__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __await__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__await__')
#
# asyncio.Future defines __await__ in its own __dict__ (true).
#   Future objects are awaitable — 'result = await future' is a core asyncio
#   pattern. Future directly defines __await__ in its class __dict__.
# asyncio.Task does NOT define __await__ in its own __dict__ (false).
#   Task is a subclass of Future and inherits __await__ from Future.__dict__.
#   The dunder is absent from Task's own __dict__.
# asyncio.Event: boolean-flag synchronization primitive; not directly awaitable
#   (callers await event.wait(), not the event itself). No __await__ in Event.__dict__.
# asyncio.Lock/Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore/Condition: async context managers;
#   callers use 'async with', not 'await'. No __await__ in their own __dict__.
# asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue: callers await get()/put() coroutines,
#   not the queue itself. No __await__ in their own __dict__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table as3496.await:
  description: "asyncio types __await__ dict-presence checks; wave 680"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: as3496

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["as3496021", operator.contains, [asyncio.Task.__dict__,             "__await__"], false]
    - ["as3496022", operator.contains, [asyncio.Future.__dict__,           "__await__"], true]
    - ["as3496023", operator.contains, [asyncio.Event.__dict__,            "__await__"], false]
    - ["as3496024", operator.contains, [asyncio.Lock.__dict__,             "__await__"], false]
    - ["as3496025", operator.contains, [asyncio.Semaphore.__dict__,        "__await__"], false]
    - ["as3496026", operator.contains, [asyncio.BoundedSemaphore.__dict__, "__await__"], false]
    - ["as3496027", operator.contains, [asyncio.Condition.__dict__,        "__await__"], false]
    - ["as3496028", operator.contains, [asyncio.Queue.__dict__,            "__await__"], false]
    - ["as3496029", operator.contains, [asyncio.PriorityQueue.__dict__,    "__await__"], false]
    - ["as3496030", operator.contains, [asyncio.LifoQueue.__dict__,        "__await__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __aenter__, __aexit__, __await__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __aenter__: true for Lock, Semaphore, Condition; false for all others.
# __aexit__:  true for Lock, Semaphore, Condition; false for all others.
# __await__:  true for Future only; false for all others.
# Total true values: 7 (Lock __aenter__+__aexit__, Semaphore __aenter__+__aexit__,
#   Condition __aenter__+__aexit__, Future __await__).
# Total false values: 23.
# asyncio.BoundedSemaphore note: BoundedSemaphore IS usable as an async context
#   manager ('async with bounded_semaphore:' works at runtime) because it inherits
#   __aenter__ and __aexit__ from Semaphore. However, those dunders do NOT appear
#   in BoundedSemaphore's own __dict__ — this wave confirms __aenter__ = false and
#   __aexit__ = false for BoundedSemaphore at the dict-contains level.
# asyncio.Task note: Task IS awaitable at runtime ('result = await task' works)
#   because it inherits __await__ from Future. However, __await__ does NOT appear
#   in Task's own __dict__ — this wave confirms __await__ = false for Task at the
#   dict-contains level.
# asyncio.Future note: Future defines __await__ directly in its own __dict__
#   (true). Future objects are the foundational awaitable in asyncio.
# asyncio.Lock/Semaphore/Condition note: these three types define both __aenter__
#   and __aexit__ in their own __dict__ — they are the primary async context
#   managers in asyncio's synchronization primitive set.
# asyncio.Event/Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue: none of these types define any
#   of the three async protocol dunders in their own __dict__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

